04529nam a22005535i 9780773589773DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735897737 a10.1515/97807735897732doi  a(DE-B1597)656995  a(OCoLC)1394872547  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDU424.5.S3b.P388 2013 7aHIS0040002bisacsh04a993.00491632231 aPatterson, Brad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnpacking the Kists :bThe Scots in New Zealand /cBrad Patterson, Jim McAloon, Tom Brooking. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (472 p.) :b6 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v23300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables, Figures, and Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tTaking Stock: New Zealand’s Scottish Migrants -- tDistinguishing Former Worlds: Who Were New Zealand’s Scottish Migrants? -- tDiaspora or Dispersion?: Scottish Settlement Patterns in New Zealand -- tSuccess in a Settler Society: The Scots in New Zealand Economic Life -- tBuilding New Worlds: Scottish Contributions to New Zealand Civil Society -- tTransforming the Landscape: Scots and the New Zealand Environment -- t“Brither Scots Shoulder tae Shoulder”: Scottish Associational Culture in New Zealand -- tHearth and Home: Cultural Traditions, Old World Customs, and New World Habits -- tOccupying the Non-Working Hours: Piety, Leisure, and Discourse -- tNew Zealand’s Place in the Scottish Diaspora and Settler Worlds -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorians have suggested that Scottish influences are more pervasive in New Zealand than in any other country outside Scotland, yet curiously New Zealand's Scots migrants have previously attracted only limited attention. A thorough and interdisciplinary work, Unpacking the Kists is the first in-depth study of New Zealand's Scots migrants and their impact on an evolving settler society. The authors establish the dimensions of Scottish migration to New Zealand, the principal source areas, the migrants' demographic characteristics, and where they settled in the new land. Drawing from extended case-studies, they examine how migrants adapted to their new environment and the extent of longevity in diverse areas including the economy, religion, politics, education, and folkways. They also look at the private worlds of family, neighbourhood, community, customs of everyday life and leisure pursuits, and expressions of both high and low forms of transplanted culture. Adding to international scholarship on migrations and cultural adaptations, Unpacking the Kists demonstrates the historic contributions Scots made to New Zealand culture by retaining their ethnic connections and at the same time interacting with other ethnic groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aScotszNew ZealandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Australia & New Zealand.2bisacsh1 aBrooking, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcAloon, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358977340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773589773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773589773/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles